00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Pratik, tell me a little bit about yourself. Where were you born? Where did you grow up? What's your background like?

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:43.000
[Guest]: I was born in Ahmedabad. I did my schooling in Ahmedabad.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:48.000
[Guest]: Did my engineering from Bangalore. That was 1999 to 2003.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:51.000
[Guest]: After that, I worked in Bangalore for three years.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:57.000
[Guest]: I worked only for startups through my career as a software engineer.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:03.000
[Guest]: In 2006, I went to the U.S. sometime in mid-2006, I think 2007.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:06.000
[Guest]: And then till 2010, I was in the U.S.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:11.000
[Guest]: Then 2010, I moved to Vietnam. And then 2010 to 2013, I was in Vietnam.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:15.000
[Guest]: And then 2013 is when I came back to Ahmedabad.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:18.000
[Guest]: And that is essentially where some of the political journey started.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.000
[Guest]: My politicization started, not the political journey.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:25.000
[Amit Varma]: But in a sense, you know, because of by virtue of the family that you're born in

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:29.000
[Amit Varma]: that your parents stayed, and I want to discuss that with you as well.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:33.000
[Amit Varma]: You were politically aware from a long while before that, right?

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:37.000
[Guest]: Definitely. The political awareness was right since I was a child, you know,

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:42.000
[Guest]: I was forced to watch the same news on multiple channels again and again.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:46.000
[Guest]: You know, because, you know, that is the time when cable TV came in, multiple channels came in.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:50.000
[Guest]: They're always watching news, you know, there was no soap operas there.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:54.000
[Guest]: And all the discussion on dinner table was always about politics.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:57.000
[Guest]: So, yes, I was very much politically aware, connected.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:03.000
[Guest]: But it's just that, you know, when you're away, then you look at things from a distance,

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:08.000
[Guest]: you're not actively involved. But once I came back to Ahmedabad in 2013,

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:13.000
[Guest]: and that is the time we started a website called Truth of Gujarat.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:16.000
[Guest]: And it was also a time when my father got cancer.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:19.000
[Guest]: So he was homebound, and both my parents were homebound.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:22.000
[Guest]: My mom had also retired by that point of time.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:27.000
[Guest]: And the three of us spent a lot of time together in those nine months till my father passed away.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:31.000
[Guest]: And that is when I sort of got a lot of dump of knowledge,

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:35.000
[Guest]: because we were all together, you know, sitting in a room, nothing to do.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:37.000
[Guest]: So we did a lot of talking.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:40.000
[Guest]: And which is why I often say that, yes, I was politically aware,

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:45.000
[Guest]: but the real politicization started during that period where Truth of Gujarat started.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:49.000
[Guest]: And when, you know, there was a lot of knowledge transfer from my parents to me.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:54.000
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about your dad, because he's obviously someone who's been a very big influence on you

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:58.000
[Amit Varma]: and a remarkable activist in his own time, for those who know about that period.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:00.000
[Guest]: Tell us a little bit about that.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:02.000
[Guest]: So my father was a physicist.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:07.000
[Guest]: He did his PhD from an institute called Physical Research Laboratory in Ahmedabad.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:10.000
[Guest]: Before that, he's in IIT Kanpur, Passau.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:13.000
[Guest]: And he got into union activities.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:18.000
[Guest]: There was a class for an employee who was kicked, and he went up to the director to complain about it.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:22.000
[Guest]: And that started a movement which started formation.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:27.000
[Guest]: I think Physical PRL was the first organization which got a union,

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:32.000
[Guest]: a scientific institute which got a union in the 70s.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:35.000
[Guest]: And then he was a postdoc at that point of time.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:39.000
[Guest]: He was terminated, fought the case, lost the case.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:44.000
[Guest]: And then eventually he did his LLB in late 80s, became a lawyer.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:50.000
[Guest]: A lot of activities at that point of time was concentrated on unions, various industrial unions,

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:54.000
[Guest]: unions like Atira, NID, IIM, etc.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:07:00.000
[Guest]: Eventually they got into civil rights movements such as housing, education, environment.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:06.000
[Guest]: And then when 2002 happened, that is when the organization saw that

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:10.000
[Guest]: the people were split along vertical lines, along communal lines,

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:15.000
[Guest]: which is when Jan Sanghash Manch, which is the primary civil liberties organization,

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:18.000
[Guest]: they decided to take part in Nanavati Commission.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:21.000
[Guest]: Then the spate of fake encounters started in Gujarat,

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:24.000
[Guest]: and many victims approached Jan Sanghash Manch.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:30.000
[Guest]: So we did multiple cases from Saurabh Uddin to Ishwar Jahan to Sadiq Jamal to Tulsi Prajapati.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:38.000
[Guest]: So my father's journey has essentially been from a union activist to a civil rights activist

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:45.000
[Guest]: to a lawyer who's fighting the cause of, you know, design communal polarization

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:48.000
[Guest]: that was sort of going on in the society.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:52.000
[Amit Varma]: And in those days, like for part of that time, of course, you were a software engineer,

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:54.000
[Amit Varma]: you were away, you went to the US, you went to Vietnam,

00:07:54.000 --> 00:08:00.000
[Amit Varma]: but was there a sense of worry for you that this is dangerous work that my parents are involved in?

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:04.000
[Amit Varma]: Or, I mean, obviously you were supportive, but were you also worried at the same time that,

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:09.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, why do they have to take such risks? And did it strike you as a kid that,

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:12.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, your father is involved in all these causes?

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:16.000
[Amit Varma]: And at one hand, it's obviously romantic that someone is fighting for the downtrodden,

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:21.000
[Amit Varma]: but on the other hand, did you ever feel that, you know, had he stuck to his physics

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:26.000
[Amit Varma]: or had he stuck to a regular career line, it could have made a material difference to your lives?

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.000
[Guest]: No, that thought never occurred.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:34.000
[Guest]: There have been times when sort of, you know, papers have been slipped under, you know,

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:37.000
[Guest]: left at my house with death threats, et cetera, for my father.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:40.000
[Guest]: But somehow it never crossed our mind.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:44.000
[Guest]: I think in all these things, the support system matters a lot.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:48.000
[Guest]: Even now, for example, I have, you know, got a phone call with a death threat,

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
[Guest]: like, you know, stop writing or we'll shoot you.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:53.000
[Guest]: This happened sometime in 2017.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:57.000
[Guest]: But, you know, we often look at people as individuals who are doing something,

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:00.000
[Guest]: but it's usually the support system around that that matters.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:05.000
[Guest]: In case of my father, it was my mom who sort of stood like a rock.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:06.000
[Guest]: And she was an activist.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:10.000
[Guest]: Her work is not as much recognized because she was a government employee

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:12.000
[Guest]: and, you know, she did not come out and open.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:16.000
[Guest]: But even now, for example, there was a legal notice from a news channel,

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:19.000
[Guest]: I wouldn't like the name, when we did a story about them.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:24.000
[Guest]: And it was my mother who said that, you know, we are not taking down the story, come what may.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:27.000
[Guest]: So it is always about support.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:30.000
[Guest]: Whenever you're doing any such work, it is the people around you,

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:33.000
[Guest]: the support system that matters the most.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:37.000
[Amit Varma]: Tell me about 2013, because you point out about how, you know,

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:41.000
[Amit Varma]: you had those nine months with your parents and you were sitting and talking a lot.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:43.000
[Amit Varma]: You described it as a dump of knowledge.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:46.000
[Amit Varma]: And that must have been very important for you,

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:51.000
[Amit Varma]: because I suppose both of them are sort of giving you all of their insights

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:54.000
[Amit Varma]: and learnings through the years.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:55.000
[Amit Varma]: What were they like?

00:09:55.000 --> 00:10:00.000
[Amit Varma]: And how did that change the way you looked at India and politics and what was happening?

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.000
[Guest]: So during that period, see, it was not like we were sitting and they were talking.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:08.000
[Guest]: That is, the knowledge transfer happened through a project called Truth of Gujarat.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:13.000
[Guest]: So on July 2nd, 2013, the Ishwar Jahan Charsheed came out.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:17.000
[Guest]: And this was the Charsheed which spoke about Kali Daadi and Safed Daadi

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:20.000
[Guest]: giving a go-ahead for the Ishwar Jahan encounter.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:26.000
[Guest]: According to Gujarat police's statement given to CBI,

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:30.000
[Guest]: it was claimed that Kali Daadi was a moniker used for Mr. Amit Shah

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:33.000
[Guest]: and Safed Daadi was a moniker used for Mr. Modi.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:38.000
[Guest]: And what happened thereafter was that even though there was such a huge revelation,

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:41.000
[Guest]: the media organizations did not really pick it up.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:43.000
[Guest]: You know, it was a huge revelation.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:47.000
[Guest]: So I suggested to my parents that let's put all the information online.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:48.000
[Guest]: We have a lot of information.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:52.000
[Guest]: Let's put it online and that is how Truth of Gujarat came about.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:56.000
[Guest]: And because I understood a bit of social media, I understood the youth a little.

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.000
[Guest]: So I said, every article has to be limited to four or five paragraphs

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:02.000
[Guest]: because people don't have the attention span per se.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:06.000
[Guest]: And that is how we started and it became extremely popular.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:13.000
[Guest]: Because again, even in 2013, that was the only sort of voice of opposition, so to say, in Gujarat.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:16.000
[Guest]: So during that process, you know, while writing articles,

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:19.000
[Guest]: while discussing articles with my father and with my mother,

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:23.000
[Guest]: that is the time, you know, the conversations happened around these articles.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:28.000
[Guest]: And it sort of gave me a lot of insight into their work, you know,

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:32.000
[Guest]: because they have worked across different issues from working with labor rights.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:37.000
[Guest]: So, for example, something as simple as, if you observe, you know,

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:39.000
[Guest]: if there's a farmer's movement, the labor do not join.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:42.000
[Guest]: If there's a labor movement, the farmers do not join.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:46.000
[Guest]: You might think outside that there are multiple common causes, but it does not happen.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:48.000
[Guest]: People fight for their own causes.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:52.000
[Guest]: And you cannot ever say that, why are you not fighting for somebody else's causes?

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:58.000
[Guest]: So things like that, you know, which otherwise it's difficult to understand and know

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:02.000
[Guest]: that why there are so many different sections in the society,

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:04.000
[Guest]: which are fighting for their own causes.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:07.000
[Guest]: But we keep talking about unity, but that does not happen.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:12.000
[Guest]: There's a reason for it. They have seen this in their...

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:15.000
[Guest]: And again, things like, you know, that if you're in a union,

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:18.000
[Guest]: you don't talk about who you're voting for, whether you're voting for Congress or BJP.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:20.000
[Guest]: They're fighting for a cause.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:24.000
[Guest]: They are not there to sort of... They are not political workers.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:26.000
[Guest]: They are fighting as laborers.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:30.000
[Guest]: So you have to recognize, you know, in what capacity is a certain individual

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:35.000
[Guest]: acting at any point in time to understand the outcomes of a movement, etc.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:38.000
[Guest]: So those are the things.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:41.000
[Guest]: Of course, there's so many things and it's been four or five years.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:43.000
[Guest]: My father passed away in 2014.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:48.000
[Guest]: But a lot of these small, small things, which I understood in conversations with them.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.000
[Amit Varma]: Was it during this time or was it earlier?

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:54.000
[Amit Varma]: Or was it something that was building up over time that you made the decision that

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:56.000
[Amit Varma]: I don't want to be a software engineer anymore.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:58.000
[Amit Varma]: I want to do this. This is more important.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.000
[Amit Varma]: What was that process like?

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:04.000
[Guest]: So the decision was not to be a software engineer.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:09.000
[Guest]: The decision... So I was working on various technologies

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:11.000
[Guest]: and these were cutting edge technologies.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:15.000
[Guest]: But what I realized over time is that none of that is going to reach the common man

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:19.000
[Guest]: for a very long time, the sort of stuff that I was working on.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:23.000
[Guest]: And this decision actually came around 2016.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:27.000
[Guest]: My mother and I, we walked 10 days from Ahmedabad to Una.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:31.000
[Guest]: There were four Dalit boys who were flogged in Una.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:34.000
[Guest]: The rally was taken out from Ahmedabad to Una.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:40.000
[Guest]: This is the rally in which Jignesh Mevani sort of came out as a leader.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:45.000
[Guest]: And during this rally, I documented the entire thing through Truth of Gujarat

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:47.000
[Guest]: in terms of videos and images.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:50.000
[Guest]: The thing was, there was only one person from national media,

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.000
[Guest]: one person from Hindustan Times.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:58.000
[Guest]: But otherwise people for the first five, six days had almost entirely ignored this rally.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:01.000
[Guest]: And, you know, when I started putting the videos and images

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:05.000
[Guest]: and they started getting retweeted and shared massively.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:09.000
[Guest]: And then eventually the media came in and it became a big thing.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:14.000
[Guest]: So that is the time I realized that what is the power of alternative media?

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:20.000
[Guest]: And I thought that I had certain skills to put some of my work in alternative media.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:25.000
[Guest]: At the same point in time, I was also working on misinformation right since 2013

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:29.000
[Guest]: because there was misinformation even in the 2014 elections,

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:32.000
[Guest]: but at a much, much smaller scale.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:36.000
[Guest]: But I was working on that and I could see an increasing trend

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:40.000
[Guest]: and especially starting end of 2015, 2016 when Jio came.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:42.000
[Guest]: So I could see a trend.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:47.000
[Guest]: And I also realized that traditional journalists do not have the skills to deal with this.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:51.000
[Guest]: Even though the skills required are, it is not very difficult.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:56.000
[Guest]: Even with a five-day training, a lot of traditional journalists will be able to bust

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:00.000
[Guest]: at least 70-80% of the things that go out on social media.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:02.000
[Guest]: But it is just that they are not trained for it.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:05.000
[Guest]: And media organizations, for media organizations, this was not a priority.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:10.000
[Guest]: So at that point of time, I thought that, you know, why not use some of my skills

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:15.000
[Guest]: and some of the experience that I gained while running Truth of Gujarat and start a portal.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:20.000
[Guest]: So the first document that we came up with was in September 2016.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:22.000
[Guest]: This was right after Una Rally.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:28.000
[Guest]: The first two points in the document as to what, there were multiple points that we had written,

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:33.000
[Guest]: but the first two points were, number one, debunk misinformation on social media.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:36.000
[Guest]: Number two, document people's struggles.

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:43.000
[Guest]: And we never ended up doing number two because number two needs finances where,

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:46.000
[Guest]: so you have to go to a state, you have to know the local language,

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:49.000
[Guest]: you have to stay, you have to pay for your own lodging, food, etc.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:52.000
[Guest]: And we did not have the resources to do that.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:56.000
[Guest]: So that is how we started with debunking misinformation.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:59.000
[Amit Varma]: So I'm going to take a brief digression here, a couple of digressions.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:00.000
[Amit Varma]: I'll come back to this.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:04.000
[Amit Varma]: But you've said a few things while you were talking about this,

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:07.000
[Amit Varma]: which have raised sort of lateral questions in me.

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:10.000
[Amit Varma]: So just indulge me while we talk about them.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:16.000
[Amit Varma]: One of the things is that when you were talking about 2002 and what happened in Gujarat

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:21.000
[Amit Varma]: and you used a phrase that there were vertical lines drawn between people.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:24.000
[Amit Varma]: And I just want to explore that a bit by which,

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:27.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm presuming you don't mean horizontal lines,

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:30.000
[Amit Varma]: which would be differentiating classes or whatever,

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:32.000
[Amit Varma]: but vertical lines between Hindu and Muslim?

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:37.000
[Guest]: Not between Hindu and Muslims, between Hindu and Muslims and between Hindus and Hindus.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:40.000
[Guest]: So, for example, again, I was not in India at this point of time.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.000
[Guest]: So all of this is what I've heard from my parents.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:46.000
[Guest]: So we had a union and various organizations.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:47.000
[Guest]: The city was burning.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:51.000
[Guest]: And one of the organizations was close to my house.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:53.000
[Guest]: So my parents walked to that place.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:55.000
[Guest]: They were having a small meeting.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:17:02.000
[Guest]: And somebody who was actually used to teach me drawing when I was a kid,

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:04.000
[Guest]: never successfully could do so.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:07.000
[Guest]: But that person, while talking about the riots,

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:08.000
[Guest]: he stood up and said,

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:12.000
[Guest]: that these people should be killed.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:16.000
[Guest]: So that is what shocked many people in the organization,

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:19.000
[Guest]: especially my parents, senior people of the organization,

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:22.000
[Guest]: that we've been running this organization for such a long time,

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:27.000
[Guest]: but we did not know that this communal hatred was so deep rooted.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:29.000
[Guest]: So vertical, yes.

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:31.000
[Guest]: If you remember 2002 riots,

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:33.000
[Guest]: if you think of the accused,

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:37.000
[Guest]: a lot of accused in urban areas were from Dalit communities.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:41.000
[Guest]: A lot of accused in the rural areas were from Adivasi communities.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:47.000
[Guest]: So essentially it was a project to bring all castes together.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:51.000
[Guest]: And it was an unnatural project in the sense that

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:55.000
[Guest]: the upper caste and lower caste are supposed to be ideologically opposed.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:58.000
[Guest]: You know, one is the, there is, you know,

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:02.000
[Guest]: Brahmins and Dalits are supposed to be opposed in different ways.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:05.000
[Guest]: But this is a project which united everybody.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:07.000
[Guest]: Which is why I say that, you know,

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:11.000
[Guest]: there was a vertical division essentially between Muslims and Hindus,

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:14.000
[Guest]: but a certain section of Hindus who still believed in certain secular values

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:15.000
[Guest]: and even between that.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:18.000
[Guest]: And we continue to see that today, this vertical polarization,

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:21.000
[Guest]: whether it is in our friends, family, et cetera,

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:23.000
[Amit Varma]: we just completely vertically divided.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:25.000
[Amit Varma]: And when you sort of look at, I mean, of course,

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:30.000
[Amit Varma]: that a whole project of superimposing a broader Hindutva identity

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:33.000
[Amit Varma]: across castes and all that is something that continues to this day

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:36.000
[Amit Varma]: and might even have been fairly successful so far.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:41.000
[Amit Varma]: But when you sort of look at what society in Gujarat was,

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:43.000
[Amit Varma]: say in 2013, when you came back,

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:45.000
[Amit Varma]: and what it was earlier when you were still studying

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:48.000
[Amit Varma]: and when you were still sort of just living there,

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:52.000
[Amit Varma]: do you think there were fundamental changes within society itself?

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:55.000
[Amit Varma]: Or do you think that those divisions, fault lines were always there,

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:59.000
[Amit Varma]: but had now been amplified and given expression?

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:03.000
[Guest]: So again, my understanding of this, as I said,

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:06.000
[Guest]: became better only after 2013.

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:08.000
[Guest]: But even when I was in school, there were riots.

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:12.000
[Guest]: So Gujarat has often very, has been a tinderbox, you know,

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:14.000
[Guest]: even after Babri Masjid demolition,

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:16.000
[Guest]: there were riots in Ahmedabad and things like that.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:20.000
[Guest]: In 1969, there were riots, which are much bigger than 2002.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:21.000
[Guest]: And that time there was a Congress government.

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:23.000
[Guest]: It was not a BJP government.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:26.000
[Guest]: And there were many Muslims who were killed.

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:29.000
[Guest]: So Gujarat has had a history,

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:33.000
[Guest]: but the polarization has definitely increased over time.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:37.000
[Guest]: And this is, for example, if you talk to people the age my mother,

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:40.000
[Guest]: so my mother often tells me this tale,

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:42.000
[Guest]: that she's from a Jain family.

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:47.000
[Guest]: But her father built a house for a friend of theirs,

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:49.000
[Guest]: a Muslim couple at that age,

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:51.000
[Guest]: because the family was not accepting.

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:55.000
[Guest]: So he built, sort of carved out a small portion in their house

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:57.000
[Guest]: where that Muslim couple could stay.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:19:59.000
[Guest]: So still that used to happen.

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:01.000
[Guest]: Now, those kinds of stories are very, very,

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:03.000
[Guest]: you don't hear those kinds of stories in Gujarat.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:07.000
[Guest]: You know, you have Juhapura where all the Muslims stay.

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:10.000
[Guest]: You know, basically they're ghettos.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:12.000
[Guest]: You know, there's so much polarization

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:16.000
[Guest]: that there's very little intermingling between different communities,

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:18.000
[Guest]: except for maybe, you know, at workplaces.

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:22.000
[Amit Varma]: But cultural intermingling is very, very minimal.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:27.000
[Amit Varma]: My next digression is both about politics and strategy

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:29.000
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that you mentioned that

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:32.000
[Amit Varma]: when your father would work with unions and so on,

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:36.000
[Amit Varma]: that one of the characteristics of unions

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:40.000
[Amit Varma]: was that all of these people would come together for a specific cause,

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:43.000
[Amit Varma]: but they wouldn't necessarily be united otherwise.

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:46.000
[Amit Varma]: Now, I suppose in one way, this can be a bug

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:49.000
[Amit Varma]: and you can say that this unity and this organization is wasted

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:51.000
[Amit Varma]: because it's only for this cause.

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:55.000
[Amit Varma]: In another way, it could be a feature because, you know,

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:58.000
[Amit Varma]: otherwise it would be impossible for them to unite for a cause

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:01.000
[Amit Varma]: if you allowed other issues to sort of divide them.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:06.000
[Amit Varma]: But quite separate from the matter of how it plays out in terms of unions,

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:10.000
[Amit Varma]: how does it play out broadly in the political space

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:13.000
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that I would imagine that

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:17.000
[Amit Varma]: a coalition of people who are, say, against fake news

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:21.000
[Amit Varma]: would be a broader coalition, would have disagreements on many things,

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:25.000
[Amit Varma]: should be what Congress or ARP or whoever, not vote at all,

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:28.000
[Amit Varma]: but would have disagreements on many other things,

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:30.000
[Amit Varma]: but could be united against falsehood.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:35.000
[Amit Varma]: So is this sort of a consideration that plays out?

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:37.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, what do you think about this?

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:39.000
[Guest]: No, two are different things.

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:43.000
[Guest]: Fighting for labor rights, etc. is a different matter altogether.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:46.000
[Guest]: There you're talking about people, you know, if there's a strike,

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:51.000
[Guest]: let's say there was a 27-day Saif-e-Kamdaa strike in August 2016,

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:57.000
[Guest]: right after UNA rally, and which means 27 days of no pay for workers.

00:21:57.000 --> 00:22:00.000
[Guest]: You know, here you're talking about people who are living on a day-to-day basis

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:04.000
[Guest]: if 27 days of no pay means disastrous for them, right?

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:08.000
[Guest]: So for them to now come and join another strike of another organization,

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:11.000
[Guest]: give up their day pay, is a different matter

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:15.000
[Guest]: as opposed to people sitting on social media and extending support.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:18.000
[Guest]: So these two cannot be compared.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:22.000
[Guest]: You can compare people on social media extending support for,

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:24.000
[Guest]: let's say, farmer's rights, you know.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:28.000
[Guest]: So there'll be urban sections of the population who would extend support

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:30.000
[Guest]: for the struggle of farmers, etc.

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:31.000
[Guest]: That could be a comparison.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:35.000
[Guest]: So yes, people do unite on a common cause,

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:40.000
[Guest]: but people fighting for different issues at the ground level

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:42.000
[Guest]: rarely ever unite.

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:43.000
[Guest]: And you can see that in politics also.

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:47.000
[Guest]: For example, and this I have again figured out by talking to people.

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:51.000
[Guest]: So for example, in Karnataka, Congress and JDS have always been

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:53.000
[Guest]: opposed to each other, right?

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:57.000
[Guest]: And now one day you ask them to come together and form a successful coalition.

00:22:57.000 --> 00:23:00.000
[Guest]: The people on the top may start sort of joining hands,

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:02.000
[Guest]: but the people who are on the ground who are all...

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.000
[Guest]: No, this is a different kind of thing.

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:07.000
[Guest]: Here it is not that the laborers and farmers are against each other,

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:09.000
[Guest]: but I'm talking about a different kind of phenomenon.

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:14.000
[Guest]: To think that the Congress and JDS workers will suddenly be happy

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:15.000
[Guest]: and working with each other.

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:17.000
[Guest]: Same with SPBSP in Uttar Pradesh.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:21.000
[Guest]: We have seen all these coalitions, these dream coalitions,

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:23.000
[Guest]: the way media projects it,

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:25.000
[Guest]: but we have seen this failing again and again and again.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:29.000
[Guest]: So there are people who are sort of concentrated on one area,

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:35.000
[Guest]: and it's very rarely that you see sort of a wide unity of masses.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:39.000
[Amit Varma]: And there's a, you know, moving on to a related issue,

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:42.000
[Amit Varma]: there's a term in public choice theory called the free rider effect,

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:46.000
[Amit Varma]: where what happens is that there might be many people who care about

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:48.000
[Amit Varma]: a particular cause that are affected by it,

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:51.000
[Amit Varma]: but most of them won't actually do anything concrete to take action

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:53.000
[Amit Varma]: or protest it, rather free ride.

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:57.000
[Amit Varma]: For example, a lot of people who may be against fake news,

00:23:57.000 --> 00:23:58.000
[Amit Varma]: may be bothered by it,

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:01.000
[Amit Varma]: and maybe they have the capacity to do some of the work themselves.

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:03.000
[Amit Varma]: They can do the reverse Google searches and whatever,

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:04.000
[Amit Varma]: they can do all of that.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:08.000
[Amit Varma]: But they instead kind of choose to free ride on say an alt news,

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:10.000
[Amit Varma]: which is sort of doing all this.

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:13.000
[Amit Varma]: So does it sometimes frustrate you that, look,

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:16.000
[Amit Varma]: I am embarked on this journey, which is so difficult,

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:19.000
[Amit Varma]: and there is a struggle and all these people express support,

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:21.000
[Amit Varma]: but in concrete terms,

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:24.000
[Amit Varma]: it's almost like there are a few people walking alone.

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:25.000
[Guest]: It does not frustrate me.

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:29.000
[Guest]: See, everybody has chosen different aims and ambitions in life.

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:33.000
[Guest]: For me, alt news is presently a very, very important project.

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:35.000
[Guest]: You're doing podcasting.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:37.000
[Guest]: This is what you are doing.

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:41.000
[Guest]: Before you're doing a podcast, you're researching several hours.

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:44.000
[Guest]: Now, in between that, you get some misinformation.

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:50.000
[Guest]: I can't expect you to go up and split a video into frames,

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:52.000
[Guest]: go and look up, oh, this is the video.

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:55.000
[Guest]: I don't think that is the right expectation.

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:57.000
[Guest]: So here we have to identify what is the problem.

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:01.000
[Guest]: The problem is that there are so many means of getting information,

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:03.000
[Guest]: but there's an easy means of getting information,

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:06.000
[Guest]: but there's no easy means of figuring out

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:08.000
[Guest]: what is the truth behind information.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:12.000
[Guest]: If you had something where, you know, you get something,

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:14.000
[Guest]: you get a video or an image on WhatsApp,

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:17.000
[Guest]: and if you could upload it to an app and the app would tell you

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:20.000
[Guest]: that this is, you know, in one tab, the app gives you an answer

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:23.000
[Guest]: that this is probably the fact check

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:25.000
[Guest]: or the real story behind this image and video,

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:27.000
[Guest]: then you're more likely to do it.

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:31.000
[Guest]: So it is the fact that people are not doing it is a problem

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:32.000
[Guest]: that needs to be solved.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:34.000
[Guest]: It is not a matter of frustration.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:36.000
[Guest]: One has to understand why are people not doing it

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:39.000
[Guest]: and what will make people do so.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:41.000
[Guest]: You know, what are the tools?

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:44.000
[Guest]: You know, what does it need for people to go from not doing it

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:45.000
[Guest]: to starting to do it?

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:47.000
[Guest]: So, yeah, it does not frustrate me really.

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:48.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:51.000
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of go back to your journey with Truth of Gujarat

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:52.000
[Amit Varma]: and then later Alt News.

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:56.000
[Amit Varma]: And you mentioned that there was some fake news already in 2014

00:25:56.000 --> 00:25:59.000
[Amit Varma]: and all of that, but it's only in 2016

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:02.000
[Amit Varma]: that sort of there was an inflection point.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:03.000
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about that.

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:04.000
[Amit Varma]: What happened in 2016?

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:07.000
[Amit Varma]: What confluence of events came together

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:09.000
[Amit Varma]: to make fake news a real threat?

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:10.000
[Guest]: Right.

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:13.000
[Guest]: So what happened in 2016 was that in November 2016,

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:15.000
[Guest]: Jio was launched.

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:18.000
[Guest]: And in anticipation of Jio being launched,

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:22.000
[Guest]: multiple telecom couriers were already dropping their rates.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:27.000
[Guest]: So the pattern that we saw was that end of 2015

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:32.000
[Guest]: and beginning of 2016, these websites which came up

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:34.000
[Guest]: and which had a lot of content,

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:36.000
[Guest]: a lot of misinformation and ads.

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:41.000
[Guest]: So people realized that there was a way to monetize this.

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:44.000
[Guest]: There's a way that now Internet is reaching

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:48.000
[Guest]: farther and farther corners of this country.

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:50.000
[Guest]: And by writing sensational stuff

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:52.000
[Guest]: and getting people to click on ads,

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:56.000
[Guest]: and a lot of these were semi-porn ads, you know.

00:26:56.000 --> 00:26:58.000
[Guest]: So Tabola kind of ad format,

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:02.000
[Guest]: you have six to nine boxes at the bottom of the article,

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:06.000
[Guest]: but a lot of that was essentially nude imagery

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:08.000
[Guest]: or semi-nude imagery.

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:13.000
[Guest]: So that is the pattern that we started seeing.

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:17.000
[Guest]: And along with that, these increasing forwards, et cetera,

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:20.000
[Guest]: multiple Facebook pages came up,

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:22.000
[Guest]: which started putting whatever was on WhatsApp

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:24.000
[Guest]: on their Facebook pages.

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:26.000
[Guest]: So essentially there were more and more people

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:28.000
[Guest]: who could be reached on social media,

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:31.000
[Guest]: and there were certain sections on the society

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:35.000
[Guest]: who realized that this is a good way to monetize this.

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:37.000
[Guest]: That is how it started, according to me.

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:40.000
[Guest]: And then there were others who saw these people,

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:44.000
[Guest]: seeing that how easily people were consuming misinformation

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:46.000
[Guest]: and saw that there is a political end to this,

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:49.000
[Guest]: that this can be used actually for a political purpose.

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:52.000
[Guest]: And that is what started.

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:55.000
[Guest]: If you remember in November 2016 when demonetization happened,

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:58.000
[Guest]: this is a different kind of rumor, but just the impact of it.

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:02.000
[Guest]: A rumor went about that shops are running out of sugar.

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:06.000
[Guest]: And there were shops which were attacked by civilians

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:09.000
[Guest]: just because of the fear that they are running out of sugar.

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:11.000
[Guest]: Now, somebody might think, you know, running out of sugar,

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:13.000
[Guest]: why would you attack a shop?

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:16.000
[Guest]: But what we did not realize was that the society

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:19.000
[Guest]: was in a stressed state because of demonetization.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:22.000
[Guest]: And, you know, it was a sort of a sudden decision

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:24.000
[Guest]: which people did not anticipate.

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:26.000
[Guest]: So then at that point of time,

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:28.000
[Guest]: they were ready to believe anything that is put out.

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:30.000
[Guest]: So there were so many rumors about demonetization,

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:33.000
[Guest]: for example, that GPS chip, right?

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:35.000
[Guest]: And people took in these rumors.

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:37.000
[Guest]: Everybody took in these rumors.

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:39.000
[Guest]: Some of the rumors even I might have believed,

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:41.000
[Guest]: you know, because we were in such a state.

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:43.000
[Guest]: So it's very important to understand

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:46.000
[Guest]: that the more stress the society gets,

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:48.000
[Guest]: you know, the more the rumors,

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:50.000
[Guest]: the more will people intake these kinds of rumors.

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:53.000
[Guest]: So those are the observations that we had

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:56.000
[Guest]: and which is why we created that document in September 2016,

00:28:56.000 --> 00:28:59.000
[Guest]: saying that, you know, we really need to sort of start

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:01.000
[Guest]: debunking misinformation, create a portal for it.

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:04.000
[Guest]: And me and Zubair, Mohammed Zubair,

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:06.000
[Guest]: both of us co-founded Alt News.

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:08.000
[Guest]: Zubair used to run a Facebook page,

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:11.000
[Guest]: a parody Facebook page called Unofficial Subramaniam Swamy.

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:13.000
[Guest]: I used to run Truth of Gujarat.

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:17.000
[Guest]: And we already had a collective following about 800,000,

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:20.000
[Guest]: between 800,000 and a million,

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:22.000
[Guest]: including Twitter and Facebook.

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:26.000
[Guest]: So we were in a unique position that we already have an audience

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:29.000
[Guest]: as opposed to many organizations who start without an audience.

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:31.000
[Guest]: And we're like, let's start putting things on a portal

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:33.000
[Guest]: and let's see what happens.

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:35.000
[Guest]: You know, one year hence, we'll see whether it works out or not.

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:37.000
[Guest]: Zubair continued to work,

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:40.000
[Guest]: but I stopped freelancing at that point in time.

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:42.000
[Guest]: And let's do this for one year,

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:44.000
[Guest]: we'll figure out whether this works or not.

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:48.000
[Guest]: But within three months, Alt News took off quite well.

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:51.000
[Amit Varma]: And you said that, you know, you told me earlier

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:54.000
[Amit Varma]: that the impetus behind Alt News was really fear.

00:29:54.000 --> 00:29:56.000
[Amit Varma]: Just elaborate on that a bit.

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:59.000
[Guest]: Yeah, so a lot of these videos,

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:02.000
[Guest]: some of the first few articles that we've written on Alt News

00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:05.000
[Guest]: are videos from Mexico, Brazil, et cetera,

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:09.000
[Guest]: being passed around claiming that these are Muslims killing Hindus.

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:12.000
[Guest]: And every time at that point of time,

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:14.000
[Guest]: when we used to see these videos,

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:17.000
[Guest]: there used to be a fear that, you know,

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:19.000
[Guest]: this is going to lead to the next riot.

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:22.000
[Guest]: If you remember Muzaffarnagar riots, that is what happened, right?

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:24.000
[Guest]: There was a video from Pakistan, which was put out,

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:26.000
[Guest]: and that led to riots.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:28.000
[Guest]: And there have been other instances.

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:31.000
[Guest]: In Pune, there was a Muslim boy, a techie, was killed

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:35.000
[Guest]: because there was a morphed image which was circulated of a Hindu idol.

00:30:35.000 --> 00:30:38.000
[Guest]: And there were riots, and this guy had nothing to do with any of this.

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:43.000
[Guest]: He was just going back to his home or to work, and he got killed.

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:45.000
[Guest]: So we were seeing that,

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:48.000
[Guest]: these manifestations of misinformation in the society.

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:51.000
[Guest]: And so that was the fear that, you know,

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:53.000
[Guest]: this video could lead to a riot.

00:30:53.000 --> 00:30:57.000
[Guest]: And, you know, you'd write really, you know, sort of put out,

00:30:57.000 --> 00:31:00.000
[Guest]: try to put it out as far as possible.

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:02.000
[Guest]: The language, even back then,

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:04.000
[Guest]: we have changed some of those articles now,

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:06.000
[Guest]: but even our language back then,

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:10.000
[Guest]: when I read back the way I had written some of those articles,

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:12.000
[Guest]: you could see the fear that, please don't share these,

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:14.000
[Guest]: you know, this is completely false.

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:16.000
[Guest]: We don't write that way anymore.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:18.000
[Guest]: We have a more professional way of writing things.

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:20.000
[Guest]: But even in the language back then,

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:22.000
[Guest]: I could see that there was a fear inside,

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:25.000
[Guest]: which is why we sort of were doing this very, very,

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:29.000
[Guest]: there was a bit of desperation in the language.

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:32.000
[Amit Varma]: And before we go deeper into the subject of fake news,

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:34.000
[Amit Varma]: I'd also like you to define it for me,

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:36.000
[Amit Varma]: because you've written eloquently about how

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:38.000
[Amit Varma]: there are different kinds of fake news as a distinction

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:41.000
[Amit Varma]: between misinformation and disinformation and so on.

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:43.000
[Guest]: Tell me a little bit about that.

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:47.000
[Guest]: So actually, we hardly ever use the phrase fake news anymore.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:49.000
[Guest]: We have gone away from using that.

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:51.000
[Guest]: I don't think I have used it even once.

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:53.000
[Amit Varma]: You haven't, I have, in fact.

00:31:53.000 --> 00:31:55.000
[Guest]: Yes, we don't use that phrase anymore.

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:59.000
[Guest]: We use misinformation and disinformation or malinformation.

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:02.000
[Guest]: So misinformation is essentially,

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:05.000
[Guest]: first, okay, disinformation is when you know something is false

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:07.000
[Guest]: and you still propagate it.

00:32:07.000 --> 00:32:10.000
[Guest]: Misinformation is you're propagating it without,

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:12.000
[Guest]: it is false, but you don't know whether you're,

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:15.000
[Guest]: it is false or not, and you're not bothered to check

00:32:15.000 --> 00:32:17.000
[Guest]: and you're still propagating it.

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:19.000
[Guest]: Those are the broad definitions.

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:21.000
[Guest]: So we usually stick to these two terms.

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:25.000
[Guest]: We don't use the, unless it is very, very specifically fake news,

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:27.000
[Guest]: that is a mainstream media is putting it out

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:29.000
[Guest]: and it is fake in nature.

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:34.000
[Guest]: Usually only then, or it has been framed in form of news

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:35.000
[Guest]: and it is completely fake.

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:38.000
[Guest]: You know, very, very few times we use the phrase fake news.

00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:40.000
[Amit Varma]: So just to sort of try and illustrate that

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:42.000
[Amit Varma]: and tell me if my illustrations are correct.

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:46.000
[Amit Varma]: So this information would be that if I am a hardcore Hindutva person

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:48.000
[Amit Varma]: and I sent out this message saying that,

00:32:48.000 --> 00:32:51.000
[Amit Varma]: look, the Muslim birth rate is nine, which someone once told me,

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:54.000
[Amit Varma]: by the way, the Muslim birth replacement rate is nine

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:56.000
[Amit Varma]: and soon they will be the majority in India.

00:32:56.000 --> 00:32:58.000
[Amit Varma]: And I know it's false, but I send it out.

00:32:58.000 --> 00:33:01.000
[Amit Varma]: That is disinformation and misinformation would be

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:04.000
[Amit Varma]: if I receive a WhatsApp forward saying shops are running out of sugar

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:06.000
[Amit Varma]: and I have no way of knowing whatever,

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:08.000
[Amit Varma]: but it seems like something I should let people know about

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:11.000
[Amit Varma]: so they can get sugar, though sugar is poison.

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:13.000
[Amit Varma]: And then I forward that out.

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:15.000
[Amit Varma]: So that is misinformation.

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:18.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you just said something which is really interesting

00:33:18.000 --> 00:33:21.000
[Amit Varma]: and I also want to now ask you about that,

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:26.000
[Amit Varma]: which is the two ways in which misinformation or disinformation originates.

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:30.000
[Amit Varma]: Like people have this impression about misinformation, disinformation,

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:32.000
[Amit Varma]: fake news, whatever, for the purpose of convenience,

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:34.000
[Amit Varma]: I'll just call it fake news for now.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:37.000
[Amit Varma]: But people have this impression about it that,

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:40.000
[Amit Varma]: oh, it's these political IT cell fake news factories

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:43.000
[Amit Varma]: which are churning these out and there are workers

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:46.000
[Amit Varma]: who have been paid to sit and write these WhatsApp messages

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:48.000
[Amit Varma]: and they are sort of forwarded out.

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:50.000
[Amit Varma]: But what you've indicated in this episode

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:53.000
[Amit Varma]: and what you once told me in a conversation we had a long time ago

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:56.000
[Amit Varma]: with regard to the Rohit Sardana case, for example,

00:33:56.000 --> 00:34:00.000
[Amit Varma]: is that there is a lot of this misinformation happens organically,

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:02.000
[Amit Varma]: that there is a market for it.

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:06.000
[Amit Varma]: And because there is a market of willing consumers for fake news,

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:12.000
[Amit Varma]: people create fake news just to sort of get clicks, make money, all of that.

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:16.000
[Amit Varma]: Is it necessary that there is a political motivation or something like that?

00:34:16.000 --> 00:34:20.000
[Guest]: I wouldn't say there's a market for consuming fake news or misinformation.

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:23.000
[Guest]: There's a market for consuming sensationalism.

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:26.000
[Guest]: A lot of media organizations indulge in that

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:29.000
[Guest]: purely because there's a market for it.

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:36.000
[Guest]: So, for example, once there was this tweet,

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:39.000
[Guest]: this social media trend called I support Rohit Sardana,

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:42.000
[Guest]: and it was claimed that there are some X number of fatwas

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:45.000
[Guest]: which were issued against Rohit Sardana.

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:48.000
[Guest]: And by evening, Rohit Sardana came out and clarified that

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:50.000
[Guest]: there's no such thing that has happened.

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:53.000
[Guest]: Please, you know, stay away from misinformation

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:55.000
[Guest]: and thank you for the support.

00:34:55.000 --> 00:35:00.000
[Guest]: So I went and dug into this and tried to figure out where this originated from.

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:05.000
[Guest]: And it took me to a website, completely unknown website,

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:08.000
[Guest]: which had first put this and then multiple of these right-wing websites

00:35:08.000 --> 00:35:09.000
[Guest]: that carried in.

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:14.000
[Guest]: Just to sort of think of that this is not limited to right-wing.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:16.000
[Guest]: It is across ideological spectrums.

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:17.000
[Guest]: Just want to put it out.

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:20.000
[Guest]: But it definitely started more in the right-wing.

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:22.000
[Guest]: Anyway, so going back to the conversation.

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:25.000
[Guest]: So I tracked this website and we wrote a story.

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:28.000
[Guest]: I found the Facebook profile of this person.

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:30.000
[Guest]: He looked like a very young kid.

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:34.000
[Guest]: And on his Facebook profile, there were two screenshots

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:39.000
[Guest]: of him getting advertising money from a couple of advertising companies.

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:43.000
[Guest]: You know, some 18,000 rupees in all, I think.

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:45.000
[Guest]: We wrote the story.

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:46.000
[Guest]: And I forgot about it.

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:50.000
[Guest]: Next day, I get a message from an anonymous WhatsApp number

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:53.000
[Guest]: saying that he said this in Hindi.

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:02.000
[Guest]: So then I got his phone number and I spoke with him

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:09.000
[Guest]: and it turned out that he was a class 12 boy who was studying in Ranchi.

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:12.000
[Guest]: His father was a farm help in a village outside Ranchi,

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:13.000
[Guest]: earning 6,000 rupees a month.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:17.000
[Guest]: And he said that to pay my expense, this is what I do.

00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:21.000
[Guest]: And interestingly, I spoke with somebody similar just a few days ago.

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:23.000
[Guest]: But this was in 2017.

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:25.000
[Guest]: And he said that you got one detail wrong.

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:27.000
[Guest]: I don't make 20,000 rupees a month.

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:29.000
[Guest]: I make 40,000 rupees a month.

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:33.000
[Guest]: But then I tried to tell him that, you know,

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:36.000
[Guest]: look, you're going to get into trouble at some point in time.

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:38.000
[Guest]: And eventually, I think he shut down the website.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:41.000
[Guest]: I don't know what he's doing at this point in time.

00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:43.000
[Guest]: And this kid said something very interesting.

00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:48.000
[Guest]: He said that only if I put this misinformation,

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:50.000
[Guest]: look, so many websites are covered.

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:53.000
[Guest]: He said it as a matter of pride that there's this other website

00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:56.000
[Guest]: called hindutva.info, which was sort of a very popular website

00:36:56.000 --> 00:36:57.000
[Guest]: at that point in time.

00:36:57.000 --> 00:37:00.000
[Guest]: And he said, look, hindutva.info has also written about it.

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:02.000
[Guest]: And he knew that it was completely false.

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:05.000
[Guest]: He's like, people only read when you write these things.

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:07.000
[Guest]: So there's a market for sensationalism.

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:11.000
[Guest]: I wouldn't say there's a market for, you know, misinformation per se.

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:14.000
[Guest]: There's a lot of misinformation in sensationalism.

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:17.000
[Amit Varma]: That's a very nuanced point because I had, in fact, assumed

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:20.000
[Amit Varma]: when I first heard the story from you that, okay, this is, you know,

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:23.000
[Amit Varma]: there's an organic demand for the, you know, fake news, so to say.

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:26.000
[Amit Varma]: But as you're pointing out, there's an organic demand for sensationalism,

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:27.000
[Amit Varma]: which has always been there.

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:30.000
[Amit Varma]: And the sensational will often be fake.

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:33.000
[Amit Varma]: And often people who are creating this news don't even care

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:35.000
[Amit Varma]: whether it's fake or real, and they don't think too hard

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:36.000
[Amit Varma]: about the consequences.

00:37:36.000 --> 00:37:40.000
[Amit Varma]: It's just that you want the clicks and all of that.

00:37:40.000 --> 00:37:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And, like, over time, as you examine different categories

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:46.000
[Amit Varma]: of misinformation and disinformation,

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:49.000
[Amit Varma]: is it always clear that what is the intent,

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:51.000
[Amit Varma]: and therefore you figure out where it originated from?

00:37:51.000 --> 00:37:55.000
[Amit Varma]: Or sometimes is it the case that the intent is only sensationalism

00:37:55.000 --> 00:37:57.000
[Amit Varma]: and there's no other intent?

00:37:57.000 --> 00:38:00.000
[Amit Varma]: For example, you know, earlier you mentioned that shops are running

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:02.000
[Amit Varma]: out of sugar, and there was that rumor during Demond.

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:05.000
[Amit Varma]: Like, where would that have originated from and why?

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:06.000
[Amit Varma]: Or is it just something that someone

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:09.000
[Guest]: Very often you can't figure out intent, and it is not always organic.

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:13.000
[Guest]: So this was organic in the sense somebody created.

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:18.000
[Guest]: But I do believe that there are individuals who are tasked to do this.

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:20.000
[Guest]: There's an organized way of putting out misinformation.

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:23.000
[Guest]: And, you know, since the time Altnew started, since the time

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:27.000
[Guest]: we wrote about certain websites, for example, the Postcard News guy,

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:29.000
[Guest]: there's a guy called Mahesh Vikram Hegde who got arrested

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:31.000
[Guest]: based on an Altnew story.

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:34.000
[Guest]: And even my thoughts about, you know, whether people should be

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:36.000
[Guest]: arrested or not have changed.

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:38.000
[Guest]: At that point of time, we wrote an article saying that it

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:41.000
[Guest]: is an achievement, and I think back, and I think that it was

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:42.000
[Guest]: a wrong thing to do.

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:47.000
[Guest]: I don't think he should have been arrested, but we can go to that later.

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:51.000
[Guest]: So what happened was that the fear that you could get arrested,

00:38:51.000 --> 00:38:53.000
[Guest]: in the U.S. you are protected by First Amendment,

00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:56.000
[Guest]: so which is why there are multiple fake news websites

00:38:56.000 --> 00:38:59.000
[Guest]: which continue there because you're not going to get arrested

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:01.000
[Guest]: for writing something.

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:03.000
[Guest]: But here, since there's a fear that you might get arrested,

00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:08.000
[Guest]: so that business which had started in 2015-2016 of writing

00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:11.000
[Guest]: communal misinformation has more or less stopped.

00:39:11.000 --> 00:39:13.000
[Guest]: You don't hear of Postcard News, etc.

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:17.000
[Guest]: There used to be this website called Dhyanik Bharat

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:18.000
[Guest]: that has also gone down.

00:39:18.000 --> 00:39:21.000
[Guest]: So that phenomenon has stopped.

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:26.000
[Guest]: So misinformation in order to make money has stopped.

00:39:26.000 --> 00:39:30.000
[Guest]: There's other kinds of misinformation like Bollywood, gossip,

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:31.000
[Guest]: you know, that kind.

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:34.000
[Guest]: But communal misinformation, knowing that it could sort of

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:38.000
[Guest]: land you in jail, I think that has come down a lot on websites

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:39.000
[Guest]: in order to make money.

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:43.000
[Guest]: But what has now increased is organized misinformation.

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:45.000
[Guest]: You look at Balakot strikes.

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:49.000
[Guest]: When Balakot strikes happened, that was one of the busiest

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:50.000
[Guest]: times for us.

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:52.000
[Guest]: I mean, there was such a spike of misinformation.

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:57.000
[Guest]: So one of them was a video game which went viral claiming that

00:39:57.000 --> 00:40:02.000
[Guest]: you can see a missile honing onto a building and sort of

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:03.000
[Guest]: blasting the building.

00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:05.000
[Guest]: And it was claimed that these are Balakot strikes.

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:09.000
[Guest]: Now the person who put out that in the first place,

00:40:09.000 --> 00:40:12.000
[Guest]: somebody does not just come across a video and say that,

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:13.000
[Guest]: okay, this is Balakot strikes.

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:18.000
[Guest]: That person knows that let me take this video and put the spin to it.

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:20.000
[Guest]: The first person who has done this.

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:23.000
[Guest]: So that is organized misinformation.

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:27.000
[Guest]: And the fact that when Balakot happened,

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:31.000
[Guest]: so there was another one which was a group of 10 images which

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:35.000
[Guest]: claimed that this is the level of devastation in Pakistan.

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:38.000
[Guest]: And it has reached literally every phone.

00:40:38.000 --> 00:40:40.000
[Guest]: I don't know if you've seen those group of 10 images,

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:43.000
[Guest]: but it has almost reached every phone saying that this is the level

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:45.000
[Guest]: of devastation, the picture of dead bodies.

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:49.000
[Guest]: What we found was I think four of them was from a heat stroke in Pakistan.

00:40:49.000 --> 00:40:52.000
[Guest]: Four of some others were from an earthquake,

00:40:52.000 --> 00:40:54.000
[Guest]: but not a single picture was a recent one.

00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:58.000
[Guest]: Now somebody did not come across these pictures and said that,

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:00.000
[Guest]: oh, these are pictures from Balakot.

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:03.000
[Guest]: Somebody put that out with that narrative.

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:06.000
[Guest]: So there are people who are thinking of these narratives and putting

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:09.000
[Guest]: out misinformation that is not organic.

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:13.000
[Guest]: Once it is out on social media, it goes around in an organic manner.

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:16.000
[Guest]: But people, there are people who are sitting there and creating

00:41:16.000 --> 00:41:19.000
[Guest]: misinformation and every pattern that you can see now,

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:22.000
[Guest]: it suggests that, you know, for example, during elections,

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:26.000
[Guest]: a lot of misinformation was targeting political leaders.

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:30.000
[Guest]: Okay, so I'll give you an example of Rajnath Singh and Rahul Gandhi.

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:35.000
[Guest]: So Rajnath Singh was at a rally and he said that,

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:40.000
[Guest]: Chowkidar chaur nahi hai, Chowkidar pure hai. Okay. And he asks the crowd

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:43.000
[Guest]: to repeat that and the crowd repeats Chowkidar pure hai.

00:41:43.000 --> 00:41:46.000
[Guest]: They cut the part where Rajnath Singh says this and they only

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:48.000
[Guest]: play the part where the crowd says it.

00:41:48.000 --> 00:41:51.000
[Guest]: Now, because you're used to hearing Chowkidar chaur hai,

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:54.000
[Guest]: you think that the crowd is saying Chowkidar chaur hai.

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:57.000
[Guest]: But they were actually saying Chowkidar pure hai and MP Congress's

00:41:57.000 --> 00:42:01.000
[Guest]: official verified Twitter handle put out this video saying that,

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:05.000
[Guest]: dekho Rajnath Singh ne kya bulwa diya. Okay.

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:08.000
[Guest]: So now somebody who's cutting it out at that point of time,

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:11.000
[Guest]: you know, I don't know if the person handling MP Congress

00:42:11.000 --> 00:42:14.000
[Guest]: handled it or somebody else, most likely somebody else.

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:17.000
[Guest]: But the person who did it knew exactly what the impact will be.

00:42:17.000 --> 00:42:21.000
[Guest]: Right. In case of Rahul Gandhi, one of the videos which was extremely viral

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:27.000
[Guest]: where Rahul Gandhi apparently says that women in UP bear 52 children

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:31.000
[Guest]: in every year they bear 52 children.

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:35.000
[Guest]: The context of the story was it is a six-year-old video where Rahul Gandhi,

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:40.000
[Guest]: this was during UPA time when UPA had started a scheme for pregnant women.

00:42:40.000 --> 00:42:44.000
[Guest]: If you have institutional delivery, they give you 7,000 or 7,200 rupees.

00:42:44.000 --> 00:42:48.000
[Guest]: If you have a home delivery, they give you 3,600 rupees.

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:51.000
[Guest]: This was, I think, funds coming from the union to state.

00:42:51.000 --> 00:42:57.000
[Guest]: And according to RTI response, the same woman's name was repeated 52 times.

00:42:57.000 --> 00:43:00.000
[Guest]: So as part of the way politicians speak, he said that

00:43:00.000 --> 00:43:05.000
[Guest]: UP mein mahila hai 52 bachche deti hai, you know, har saal.

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:09.000
[Guest]: And only that was cut off, you know, that 52 bachche.

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:11.000
[Guest]: And that became so viral.

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:17.000
[Guest]: The funny thing was, so viral to the point that Haryana CM ML Khattar

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:19.000
[Guest]: said that in a speech leading to elections.

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:23.000
[Guest]: There was a BJP candidate from Madhya Pradesh.

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:25.000
[Guest]: I forget which constituency.

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:29.000
[Guest]: He went and said the same thing that Rahul Gandhi ne kaha hai ki

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:32.000
[Guest]: UP mein 52 bachche dete hai mahila hai.

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:35.000
[Guest]: What the folks in Congress did was cut his statement.

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:39.000
[Guest]: So now it would seem that he's saying that UP mein 52 bachche dete hai mahila hai.

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:41.000
[Guest]: And then that second video became viral.

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:43.000
[Guest]: This is nuts.

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:50.000
[Guest]: So again, but people who are doing this and now on, which is why, you know,

00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:53.000
[Guest]: earlier I made that it is on both sides of the ideological spectrum.

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:58.000
[Guest]: They know that there is this fault line in our democracy where there is

00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:01.000
[Guest]: a huge lack of digital literacy.

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:05.000
[Guest]: They know that people are not in a position to figure out whether

00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:06.000
[Guest]: somebody said this or not.

00:44:06.000 --> 00:44:11.000
[Guest]: When you cut a clip like that, very convincingly, people will,

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:15.000
[Guest]: there's a huge section of population which will fall for it.

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:19.000
[Guest]: And they have at this point of time, again, I keep going back to saying

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:23.000
[Guest]: that we have not given people tools to figure out what is true, what is not.

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:26.000
[Guest]: We have given them a lot of tools to consume information.

00:44:26.000 --> 00:44:28.000
[Guest]: We have not given them a single tool.

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:31.000
[Guest]: There's not a single tool on the phone which will tell you that,

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:33.000
[Guest]: look, this is not true.

00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:34.000
[Guest]: This is false.

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:39.000
[Amit Varma]: And as we progress in the episode, I will ask you about the Alt News app,

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:41.000
[Amit Varma]: which I downloaded yesterday.

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And I would encourage all my listeners to download the app and try it out.

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:47.000
[Amit Varma]: But before we do that, let's talk about organized misinformation

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:48.000
[Amit Varma]: a little bit more now.

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:52.000
[Amit Varma]: Like, at some point, perhaps around 2016, perhaps afterwards,

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:56.000
[Amit Varma]: these guys realize at a political level that organized misinformation

00:44:56.000 --> 00:44:57.000
[Amit Varma]: is the way to go.

00:44:57.000 --> 00:45:00.000
[Amit Varma]: People are gullible for sensationalism, so you make anything sensational,

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:02.000
[Amit Varma]: they'll believe it and blah, blah, blah.

00:45:02.000 --> 00:45:04.000
[Amit Varma]: And you have these factories set up.

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:07.000
[Amit Varma]: And I assume that the ruling party's factory would have been there first

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:08.000
[Amit Varma]: and would have been sort of much better.

00:45:08.000 --> 00:45:09.000
[Amit Varma]: And now everyone does it.

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:11.000
[Amit Varma]: Perhaps it's like a hygiene factor.

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:12.000
[Amit Varma]: All parties have to do it.

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:15.000
[Amit Varma]: Otherwise, you can't survive in the information battle.

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:19.000
[Amit Varma]: But, like, from what you know, what is it like?

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:21.000
[Amit Varma]: Like, how organized are they?

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:22.000
[Amit Varma]: How well manned are they?

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:23.000
[Amit Varma]: What are their processes?

00:45:23.000 --> 00:45:27.000
[Amit Varma]: Like, do they just watch videos continuously and news continuously

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:31.000
[Amit Varma]: and decide, okay, we can give it the spin?

00:45:31.000 --> 00:45:36.000
[Amit Varma]: Do they have strategic imperatives, heuristics by which they pick things?

00:45:36.000 --> 00:45:39.000
[Guest]: I have no insight into that at all.

00:45:39.000 --> 00:45:43.000
[Guest]: There's no  and that is where I think we have sort of lacked,

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:47.000
[Guest]: because, you know, a lot of us don't come from a journalistic background.

00:45:47.000 --> 00:45:50.000
[Guest]: All of that needs actually getting into these places

00:45:50.000 --> 00:45:52.000
[Guest]: and figuring out how things work.

00:45:52.000 --> 00:45:55.000
[Guest]: That is something that we have not worked at.

00:45:55.000 --> 00:45:59.000
[Guest]: But, you know, a six-year-old video, and the speech was an hour-long speech.

00:45:59.000 --> 00:46:04.000
[Guest]: For somebody to find that five-second clip in an hour-long video

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:07.000
[Guest]: and put that out, that means somebody is sitting and, you know,

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:11.000
[Guest]: looking at all these things, seeing how something can be taken out.

00:46:11.000 --> 00:46:15.000
[Guest]: So, somebody is spending a lot of time, and somebody has been tasked to do it.

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:19.000
[Guest]: But how exactly this is happening, how people are being paid,

00:46:19.000 --> 00:46:24.000
[Guest]: where are they sitting, who's doing this, we have no insight into whatsoever.

00:46:24.000 --> 00:46:25.000
[Amit Varma]: And, in fact, two thoughts strike me here.

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:29.000
[Amit Varma]: And one is that it's really, I have to say here, a failure of journalism.

00:46:29.000 --> 00:46:32.000
[Amit Varma]: This is something that our mass media should really 

00:46:32.000 --> 00:46:35.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, this is basic investigative journalism.

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:38.000
[Amit Varma]: It's probably the most important story of our times

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:41.000
[Amit Varma]: in terms of the threats that our democracy faces.

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's astonishing that some embedded reporter somewhere

00:46:44.000 --> 00:46:46.000
[Amit Varma]: hasn't done a journalistic story on this.

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:50.000
[Amit Varma]: I think Swati Chaturvedi, of course, wrote a book about the trolls of the BJP.

00:46:50.000 --> 00:46:52.000
[Amit Varma]: But that's, like, kind of different.

00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:55.000
[Amit Varma]: And I recorded an episode last week with Akshay Mukul,

00:46:55.000 --> 00:46:57.000
[Amit Varma]: who's written the book on the Gita Press, which 

00:46:57.000 --> 00:47:00.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I don't know which of these episodes will get released first.

00:47:00.000 --> 00:47:05.000
[Amit Varma]: But  and what struck me during that episode with him is

00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:09.000
[Amit Varma]: that this whole mission of spreading misinformation

00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:12.000
[Amit Varma]: with strategic and tactical intent is not something

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:14.000
[Amit Varma]: that has happened because of technology.

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:16.000
[Amit Varma]: Perhaps it's been amplified by technology today,

00:47:16.000 --> 00:47:18.000
[Amit Varma]: enabled at a much larger scale.

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:20.000
[Amit Varma]: But right from the early days of the Gita Press

00:47:20.000 --> 00:47:24.000
[Amit Varma]: and their monthly journal Kalyan, which was set up in 1926,

00:47:24.000 --> 00:47:26.000
[Amit Varma]: it has been a regular thing.

00:47:26.000 --> 00:47:28.000
[Amit Varma]: The editor of Kalyan, Hanuman Prasad Poddar,

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:31.000
[Amit Varma]: used to write editorials which had fake news,

00:47:31.000 --> 00:47:34.000
[Amit Varma]: whether it's about Hindu women being abducted and raped or whatever.

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:37.000
[Amit Varma]: And this information, as you put it, not misinformation,

00:47:37.000 --> 00:47:40.000
[Amit Varma]: with a specific malafide intent,

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:44.000
[Amit Varma]: and it would seem technology has just taken it to a whole new level.

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:47.000
[Amit Varma]: And is it the case, as people often say,

00:47:47.000 --> 00:47:52.000
[Amit Varma]: that it's far easier to spread misinformation

00:47:52.000 --> 00:47:56.000
[Amit Varma]: than to actually then spread the fact-checking of it?

00:47:56.000 --> 00:47:58.000
[Amit Varma]: Fake news travels faster than fact-checking.

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:00.000
[Amit Varma]: Is that true? What are your thoughts?

00:48:00.000 --> 00:48:02.000
[Guest]: I'm not ready to buy that story.

00:48:02.000 --> 00:48:04.000
[Guest]: Yes, there has been research done in this.

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:08.000
[Guest]: Science, a very popular science magazine, Science,

00:48:08.000 --> 00:48:11.000
[Guest]: put out that tweets which have misinformation,

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:13.000
[Guest]: they sort of go much further.

00:48:13.000 --> 00:48:16.000
[Guest]: But again, I keep coming back to the thing

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:19.000
[Guest]: that where is the... you not enable people.

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:21.000
[Guest]: You know, we have seen...

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:23.000
[Guest]: So, for example, the case of vaccination.

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:26.000
[Guest]: There was a time when there were people

00:48:26.000 --> 00:48:29.000
[Guest]: who were dying of certain common ailments

00:48:29.000 --> 00:48:32.000
[Guest]: which now are gone because of vaccination.

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:35.000
[Guest]: And the society and the governments across the world,

00:48:35.000 --> 00:48:37.000
[Guest]: they took it upon themselves to spread the word.

00:48:37.000 --> 00:48:41.000
[Guest]: Now, even somebody who doesn't have any idea about vaccination,

00:48:41.000 --> 00:48:44.000
[Guest]: that person goes and gets their child vaccinated.

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:46.000
[Guest]: They have no clue, but they've just been told

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:49.000
[Guest]: that you have to vaccinate your child, right?

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:53.000
[Guest]: So, I do believe that once you enable people enough,

00:48:53.000 --> 00:48:57.000
[Guest]: there is a way to sort of push back on misinformation.

00:48:57.000 --> 00:48:59.000
[Guest]: Yes, there are biases.

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:01.000
[Guest]: It may not be a one-on-one example

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:03.000
[Guest]: of what I'm saying with vaccination,

00:49:03.000 --> 00:49:05.000
[Guest]: but there are certain...

00:49:05.000 --> 00:49:07.000
[Guest]: And people have certain biases,

00:49:07.000 --> 00:49:09.000
[Guest]: so they're more likely to believe

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:11.000
[Guest]: one misinformation over another.

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:13.000
[Guest]: We have all those challenges,

00:49:13.000 --> 00:49:15.000
[Guest]: but over the past two and a half years,

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:18.000
[Guest]: we have seen that people are willing to go

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:20.000
[Guest]: beyond what their inherent biases are.

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:22.000
[Guest]: We have had about 10 million views,

00:49:22.000 --> 00:49:24.000
[Guest]: or more than 10 million views.

00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:27.000
[Guest]: During the election time, only we had about 4 million views

00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:29.000
[Guest]: over the past four months.

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:33.000
[Guest]: And I think there are at least a good 50,000 to 100,000 people

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:36.000
[Guest]: who read Alt News on a regular basis,

00:49:36.000 --> 00:49:38.000
[Guest]: who may not be consuming every story,

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:40.000
[Guest]: but consume multiple stories.

00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:42.000
[Guest]: And I think that I have seen these people.

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:45.000
[Guest]: I know that if you look at their Twitter timeline, et cetera,

00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:48.000
[Guest]: you know that they support a particular dispensation,

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:51.000
[Guest]: or they are against a certain dispensation, either of them.

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:53.000
[Guest]: But I have seen many of them, people,

00:49:53.000 --> 00:49:55.000
[Guest]: go against their inherent biases

00:49:55.000 --> 00:49:58.000
[Guest]: and tag Alt News on Twitter or other places.

00:49:58.000 --> 00:50:00.000
[Guest]: Pratik, can you check, is this true?

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:02.000
[Guest]: Alt News, can you check, is this true?

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:04.000
[Guest]: So, I think there is a way

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:07.000
[Guest]: of creating critical thought in the society

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:09.000
[Guest]: when some person is told again and again

00:50:09.000 --> 00:50:11.000
[Guest]: that, look, what you got yesterday,

00:50:11.000 --> 00:50:14.000
[Guest]: what you got the day before yesterday, et cetera, is false.

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:16.000
[Guest]: And when you do that again and again,

00:50:16.000 --> 00:50:18.000
[Guest]: there is a point in time when that person will be,

00:50:18.000 --> 00:50:21.000
[Guest]: okay, let me first check whether this is true or false or not.

00:50:21.000 --> 00:50:24.000
[Guest]: And I believe that that is the model

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:27.000
[Guest]: that we are hoping can be replicated on a larger scale.

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:30.000
[Guest]: And once that is done, you know, at this point of time,

